eady ran the transform-job-recovery scenario and presumably fixed the transform while leaving the configmap in place, I need to figure out what state the previous agent left things in before stage 08 started.\n\nLooking back at stage 06, the precondition would have checked if pods were running (they were, so skip apply) and if the configmap exists (it does, so skip apply again). The configmap was originally created in stage 02 when the elasticsearch namespace was first set up, and the fault—scaling es-transform to zero—was injected then. The agent in stage 02 would have fixed that fault.\n\nNow I'm realizing that since the `transform_scenario_fixture` apply only runs when the configmap doesn't exist, the fault injection only happens in stage 02. For stages 04, 06, and 08, the configmap persists from stage 02, so the apply is skipped and no fault gets re-injected. This means the transform could be in different states depending on what happened in the previous stages.\n\nLooking at the current cluster state, the transform is already started with checkpoint 3, and es-transform-0 is running with capacity available. Since I'm the agent for stage 08 and haven't submitted anything yet, I need to check whether the oracle would pass—the checkpoint is already beyond checkpoint_before (3 > 0), but I should verify by checking if checkpoint_before was captured when the fault was active.\n\nThe fixture script waits up to 30 iterations for the checkpoint to reach at least 1 before saving it to the configmap, but if that never happens, it falls back to setting checkpoint_before to 0. The fact that checkpoint_before is 0 is suspicious—it suggests the fixture timed out waiting for the transform to complete its first checkpoint, which could mean the fault was already active and blocking progress when the fixture ran.\n\nNow the current checkpoint is 3, which is greater than 0, so the oracle check should pass. But I need to verify whether the transform is actually healthy and still adv